name: 5-methylbenzoxazole
Reason: 5-methylbenzoxazole has a melting point that we can compare to benzene's melting point of 5.5°C (according to the CRC Handbook of Chemistry and Physics, 49th Edition, 1968-1969). The basic unit for our comparison will be benzene, which has a melting point of 5.5°C (according to the CRC Handbook of Chemistry and Physics, 49th Edition, 1968-1969). The structural modifications we need to consider are the presence of a methyl group linked in a linear fashion. The methyl group introduces a rigid structure, which can participate in hydrogen bonding, raising the melting point by approximately +10°C.
